# Git and Version Control

## Branching Strategy (GitHub Flow)

```
main              ← production-ready, always deployable
  └── feat/...    ← new features
  └── fix/...     ← bug fixes
  └── chore/...   ← tooling, deps, config
  └── refactor/...← code restructuring (no behavior change)
  └── docs/...    ← documentation only
```

- `main` is the single source of truth — never commit directly
- All work happens in short-lived branches off `main`
- Branch naming: `{type}/{short-description}` in `kebab-case` (e.g., `feat/resume-parser`)
- Delete branches after merge

## Commit Messages (Conventional Commits)

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>

[optional body]
```

| Type | When |
|------|------|
| `feat` | New feature or capability |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | Code change that doesn't fix a bug or add a feature |
| `chore` | Build, deps, CI config, tooling |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `test` | Adding or updating tests |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `style` | Formatting, whitespace (no logic change) |

- **Scope**: module or feature affected (e.g., `feat(auth): add OAuth login`)
- **Description**: imperative mood, lowercase, no period, max 72 chars
- **Body**: explain *why*, not *what* — the diff shows what changed
- One logical change per commit — don't bundle unrelated changes

## Pull Request Standards

- Title mirrors the primary commit: `feat(matching): add skill extraction service`
- Description includes: **Summary** (what and why), **Test plan** (how to verify)
- Keep PRs small — under 400 lines changed when possible
- Self-review the diff before requesting review
- All CI checks must pass before merge
- Squash merge to `main` to keep history clean

## .gitignore Essentials

```
node_modules/
.next/
.env
.env.local
.env*.local
*.tsbuildinfo
coverage/
dist/
.vercel/
```

## Release Versioning

- Follow SemVer (`MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`) when publishing releases
- MVP phase: `0.x.y` — no stable API contract yet
- Tag releases on `main`: `v0.1.0`, `v0.2.0`, etc.
